    pushback: { challenge: "What if each boat can hold up to 3 people?", options: ["More complex: greedy with 3-pointer or DP. Optimal greedy for 3-person boats: pair heaviest with two lightest if possible. O(n log n) greedy still works with 3 pointers.","Same two-pointer","Brute force required"], correct: 0, explanation: "3-person boats: try heaviest with two lightest first (h+l1+l2≤limit), else try heaviest with lightest (h+l≤limit), else solo. Three-pointer approach. Still O(n log n) greedy — provably optimal but analysis is more involved." },
    followup: { question: "What if boats can hold unlimited people but have a weight limit?", options: ["Greedy: sort descending, use BFD (Best-Fit Decreasing) bin packing. NP-hard in general but approximation algorithms exist. Not solvable exactly in polynomial time.","Same two-pointer — just keep adding","Always 1 boat"], correct: 0, explanation: "Unlimited people per boat = bin packing = NP-hard. Two-pointer greedy doesn't apply (no 2-person constraint). Best-Fit Decreasing gives a 1.5× approximation. Exact solution: exponential." },
